  <main>
    <section class="story">
      <p>At 21, Rahul got his first job in an IT firm. Excited by his newfound independence, he quickly applied for a credit card and bought the latest gadgets. But by the end of the year, he found himself struggling with debt due to high interest rates on missed payments.</p>

      <h2>How Rahul Turned It Around:</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Financial Literacy Program:</strong> Rahul enrolled in an online youth financial literacy program offered by his company.</li>
        <li><strong>Interactive Learning:</strong> He completed quizzes and watched videos explaining the implications of credit card interest and fees.</li>
        <li><strong>Credit Calculator:</strong> The program included a credit calculator to show Rahul the true cost of missing payments and how to avoid falling into debt.</li>
        <li><strong>Debt Repayment Strategy:</strong> Rahul used the learning to create a strategy to pay off his credit card debt systematically.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Results After One Year:</h2>
      <p>Rahul cleared his credit card debt, improved his credit score, and began investing in mutual funds and SIPs (Systematic Investment Plans). He also started using credit more wisely, avoiding high-interest debt and paying his bills on time.</p>

      <h2>Takeaway:</h2>
      <p>Early financial education can help avoid mistakes, improve financial literacy, and create a foundation for smarter credit management.</p>
